One of the commonest figures employed in the Letters is that drawn from heat and cold,—the former indicating activity, the latter inertia: e.g. illi rumores de comitiis Transpadanorum Cumarum tenus caluerunt (Cael, Fam.8. 1. 2); cum Romae a iudiciis sorum refrixerit (Ast. 1. 1. 2); scripsi Curionem valde frigere, iam calet (Cael, Fam. 8. 6. 5). 100. Polite Plarasa. Such polite phrases as si me amas (e.g. Vatia, Fam, 5. 9. 1), amabo tc (e.g. Cael, Fam. 8. 6. 5), and such terms oi endearment as mel ac deliciae tuae (Cael, Fam. 8. 8. ι), are naturally of frequent occurrence. Appar- ently the Plautiae sis (siais) and sodes are not used. C I. also notes to nostri amares, Epist. VII. 2, si meamus, Epist. XIII. 3, and molestum, Epist. XVIII. 10.

101. Pleanasm. While aiming at brevigy in some caseS, in others familiar speech indulges itself in duplicative or pleonastic expressions for the sake of emphasis or distinct- ness‚ in much the same way as it employs extravagant language. Instances from the Letters are rursus reducere (Balbus Att. 8. 15a. 1) ; malle patius (Cato, Fam. 15. 5. 2); nostra iudicia . . . existimamus (Balbus and OppiuS, Att. 9. ya. 1), ostentare crebro (Dolabella, Fam. 9. 9. 2).
